<i>DORA OVER PA: This is Dora
Bailey, ladies and gentlemen...</i>


8
00:01:42.115 --> 00:01:46.161
<i>talking to you from the front of
the Chinese Theater in Hollywood.</i>


9
00:01:46.202 --> 00:01:49.702
<i>What a night, ladies and
gentlemen. What a night!</i>


10
00:01:49.789 --> 00:01:54.335
Every star in Hollywood is here to
make Monumental Pictures' premiere...


11
00:01:54.377 --> 00:01:59.423
of <i>The Royal Rascal</i>,
the outstanding event of 1927.


12
00:01:59.424 --> 00:02:01.501
Everyone is
breathlessly awaiting...


13
00:02:01.551 --> 00:02:05.151
the arrival of Lina Lamont
and Don Lockwood.


14
00:02:05.722 --> 00:02:07.549
Look who's arriving now.

15
00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:10.393
It's that famous "zip"
girl of the screen...


16
00:02:10.435 --> 00:02:12.637
the darling of the flapper set...

17
00:02:12.687 --> 00:02:14.813
Zelda Zanders!

18
00:02:14.814 --> 00:02:16.015
(CHEERING)

19
00:02:16.024 --> 00:02:18.693
Zelda! Zelda!

20
00:02:18.985 --> 00:02:23.190
DORA: Her new red-hot pash,
J. Cumberland Spendrill III...


21
00:02:23.239 --> 00:02:26.443
that well-known eligible bachelor.

22
00:02:26.493 --> 00:02:31.824
Zelda's had so much unhappiness,
I hope this time it's really love.


23
00:02:32.499 --> 00:02:36.919
And here comes that
exotic star, Olga Mara!


24
00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:39.129
ALL: Ooh.

25
00:02:39.130 --> 00:02:44.052
And her new husband,
the Baron de la Bonnet de la Toulon.


26
00:02:44.219 --> 00:02:48.847
They've been married two months already,
but still as happy as newlyweds.


27
00:02:48.848 --> 00:02:50.470
(CAR HORN TOOTING)

28
00:02:50.475 --> 00:02:54.019
Well, well, well. 
It's Cosmo Brown!

29
00:02:54.020 --> 00:02:55.854
(CROWD CHEERING)

30
00:02:55.855 --> 00:02:57.398
(CROWD GROANS)

31
00:03:00.777 --> 00:03:02.695
Cosmo is Don's best friend.

32
00:03:02.737 --> 00:03:05.235
He plays the piano on the
set for Don and Lina...


33
00:03:05.281 --> 00:03:08.951
to get them into those
romantic moods!


34
00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:11.328
Oh, folks, this is it. This is it!

35
00:03:11.329 --> 00:03:13.907
(POLICE SIRENS WAILING)

36
00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:15.708
(ALL CHEERING)

37
00:03:18.419 --> 00:03:22.749
The stars of tonight's picture,
those romantic lovers of the screen...


38
00:03:22.799 --> 00:03:25.593
Don Lockwood and Lina Lamont!

39
00:03:25.844 --> 00:03:27.796
(CROWD CHEERING)

40
00:03:31.391 --> 00:03:35.016
Ladies and gentlemen, when you
look at this gorgeous couple...


41
00:03:35.061 --> 00:03:38.765
it's no wonder they're a household
name all over the world.


42
00:03:38.773 --> 00:03:41.101
Like "bacon and eggs."

43
00:03:41.776 --> 00:03:44.604
"Lockwood and Lamont."

44
00:03:46.906 --> 00:03:50.324
Don, tell me confidentially,
are these rumors true...


45
00:03:50.325 --> 00:03:53.154
that wedding bells are soon
to ring for you and Lina?


46
00:03:53.204 --> 00:03:56.497
Lina and I have no statement
to make at the present time.


47
00:03:56.498 --> 00:03:57.951
We're just good friends.

48
00:03:57.959 --> 00:04:02.164
You've come a long way together.
Won't you tell us how it happened?


49
00:04:02.213 --> 00:04:05.631
Lina and I have made a number
of pictures together...


50
00:04:05.632 --> 00:04:09.258
Oh, no, no, Don. I want your
story from the beginning.


51
00:04:09.304 --> 00:04:12.428
Dora, not in front
of all these people!


52
00:04:12.473 --> 00:04:14.266
(CROWD CHEERS)

53
00:04:15.810 --> 00:04:18.638
The story of your success
is an inspiration...


54
00:04:18.688 --> 00:04:21.141
to young people all over the world.

55
00:04:21.357 --> 00:04:22.774
Please!

56
00:04:22.859 --> 00:04:24.982
(CROWD CHEERING)

57
00:04:26.196 --> 00:04:28.945
Well, to begin with,
any story of my career...


58
00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:32.990
would have to include my
lifelong friend, Cosmo Brown.


59
00:04:32.994 --> 00:04:35.996
We were kids together, grew
up together, worked together.


60
00:04:35.997 --> 00:04:37.198
Yes?

61
00:04:37.832 --> 00:04:42.959
Well, Dora, I've had one motto
which I've always lived by:


62
00:04:43.379 --> 00:04:46.503
"Dignity. Always dignity."

63
00:04:46.966 --> 00:04:51.342
This was instilled in me by Mum
and Dad from the very beginning.


64
00:04:51.387 --> 00:04:54.841
They sent me to the finest
schools, including dancing school.


65
00:04:54.849 --> 00:04:57.177
That's where I first met Cosmo.

66
00:04:57.227 --> 00:05:01.682
And with him, I used to perform for
Mum and Dad's society friends.


67
00:05:01.689 --> 00:05:04.392
(HARMONICA PLAYING)

68
00:05:09.155 --> 00:05:12.029
<i>DON: They used to make
such a fuss over me.</i>


69
00:05:12.075 --> 00:05:17.031
<i>If I was very good, I was allowed to
accompany Mum and Dad to the theater.</i>


70
00:05:17.080 --> 00:05:19.282
<i>They brought me up on Shaw...</i>

71
00:05:19.332 --> 00:05:22.331
<i>Moli√®re, the finest
of the classics.</i>


72
00:05:23.670 --> 00:05:26.714
To this was added rigorous
musical training...


73
00:05:26.715 --> 00:05:29.087
at the Conservatory of Fine Arts.

74
00:05:29.217 --> 00:05:32.216
(UPBEAT JAZZ TUNE PLAYING)

75
00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:38.760
<i>We rounded out our apprenticeship
at an exclusive dramatics academy.</i>


76
00:05:39.811 --> 00:05:41.809
<i>And at all times...</i>

77
00:05:41.854 --> 00:05:43.727
<i>the motto remained...</i>

78
00:05:44.023 --> 00:05:45.270
<i>"...Dignity."</i>

79
00:05:45.316 --> 00:05:47.439
<i>"Always dignity."</i>

80
00:05:49.404 --> 00:05:53.484
<i>In a few years, we were ready to
embark on a dance concert tour.</i>


81
00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:57.825
<i>We played the finest symphonic
halls in the country.</i>


82
00:05:58.621 --> 00:06:00.581
<i>(SINGING) Fit as a fiddle
And ready for love.</i>


83
00:06:00.623 --> 00:06:03.166
<i>I can jump over
The moon up above.</i>


84
00:06:03.167 --> 00:06:05.961
<i>Fit as a fiddle
And ready for love.</i>


85
00:06:07.338 --> 00:06:09.336
<i>Haven't a worry
Haven't a care.</i>


86
00:06:09.382 --> 00:06:11.801
<i>Feelin' like a feather
That's floatin' on air.</i>


87
00:06:11.802 --> 00:06:14.754
<i>Fit as a fiddle
And ready for love.</i>


88
00:06:15.596 --> 00:06:20.097
<i>Soon the church bells will be ringin'
And a march with Ma and Pa.</i>


89
00:06:20.143 --> 00:06:22.311
<i>How the church bells
will be ringin'.</i>


90
00:06:22.353 --> 00:06:25.056
<i>With a hey-nonny-nonny
And a hot-cha-cha.</i>


91
00:06:25.064 --> 00:06:27.107
<i>Hi diddle diddle
My baby's okay.</i>


92
00:06:27.150 --> 00:06:29.648
<i>Ask me a riddle
I'm happy to say.</i>


93
00:06:29.652 --> 00:06:32.605
<i>Fit as a fiddle
And ready for love</i>


94
00:07:29.504 --> 00:07:30.705
(AUDIENCE BOOING)

95
00:07:30.755 --> 00:07:33.298
<i>DON:
Audiences everywhere adored us.</i>


96
00:07:33.299 --> 00:07:34.500
MAN: Get out of here!

97
00:07:35.718 --> 00:07:39.047
<i>DON: Finally we decided to
come to sunny California.</i>


98
00:07:39.639 --> 00:07:42.592
<i>We were stranded... We were
staying here, resting up...</i>


99
00:07:42.642 --> 00:07:45.937
<i>when offers from the movie
studios started pouring in.</i>


100
00:07:45.978 --> 00:07:50.558
<i>We sorted them out and decided
to favor Monumental Pictures.</i>


101
00:07:50.775 --> 00:07:54.443
Dexter: Lina, you hate him.
Resist him. Keep that mood music going.


102
00:07:54.444 --> 00:07:56.943
Now, Phil, you come in.
Keep on grinding.


103
00:07:56.989 --> 00:08:01.740
Now you see her. Now here's the bit,
Bert, where you get it on the jaw.


104
00:08:02.412 --> 00:08:03.613
Cut!

105
00:08:03.663 --> 00:08:05.740
No, no! That wasn't right!

106
00:08:05.790 --> 00:08:10.291
You were supposed to go over the bar and
crash into the glasses! Try it again!


107
00:08:10.294 --> 00:08:12.371
Okay, Bert? Bert!

108
00:08:12.422 --> 00:08:14.670
Oh, that's swell, just swell.

109
00:08:14.674 --> 00:08:16.842
Take him away, fellas!

110
00:08:16.843 --> 00:08:20.764
You'll be all right. We've lost
more stuntmen on these pictures...


111
00:08:20.805 --> 00:08:23.849
It'll take hours to get a new
one from Central Casting.


112
00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:26.052
Mr. Dexter, I can do that.

113
00:08:26.102 --> 00:08:29.055
- You? You're a musician.
- That's a moot point.


114
00:08:29.063 --> 00:08:31.061
No kidding! What's your name?

115
00:08:31.107 --> 00:08:33.901
Don Lockwood, but the
fellas call me "Donald."


116
00:08:33.943 --> 00:08:36.817
Wise guy, huh? Okay. I'll try you.

117
00:08:36.863 --> 00:08:38.905
Get this guy into Bert's suit!

118
00:08:38.906 --> 00:08:43.703
And remember, Lockwood, you might
be trading that fiddle in for a harp.


119
00:08:45.705 --> 00:08:46.997
DEXTER: Camera!

120
00:08:47.832 --> 00:08:50.751
Phil, come in. Now you
see him. That's it.


121
00:08:50.793 --> 00:08:53.462
Now, here's where you
get it right on the jaw.


122
00:08:55.256 --> 00:08:56.457
Cut!

123
00:08:56.466 --> 00:08:58.134
That was wonderful!

124
00:08:59.719 --> 00:09:02.047
Got any more little
chores you want done?


125
00:09:02.096 --> 00:09:03.422
Plenty!

126
00:09:07.602 --> 00:09:09.054
Okay.

127
00:09:29.415 --> 00:09:32.959
<i>DON: My roles in these
films were urbane...</i>


128
00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:34.503
<i>sophisticated...</i>

129
00:09:34.504 --> 00:09:35.705
<i>suave.</i>

130
00:09:38.466 --> 00:09:41.465
And of course, all through
those pictures...


131
00:09:41.469 --> 00:09:45.138
Lina was, as always,
an inspiration to me.


132
00:09:45.139 --> 00:09:47.091
Warm and helpful.

133
00:09:47.266 --> 00:09:49.093
A real lady.

134
00:09:52.855 --> 00:09:56.480
Hello, Miss Lamont. I'm Don
Lockwood, the stuntman.


135
00:09:58.402 --> 00:10:01.230
It was a thrill working
with you, Miss Lamont.


136
00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:02.697
DEXTER: Hey, Don.

137
00:10:02.865 --> 00:10:05.818
Meet the producer of the
picture, R.F. Simpson.


138
00:10:05.826 --> 00:10:09.826
I just saw some rushes and asked
Dexter who the stuntmen were.


139
00:10:09.872 --> 00:10:14.293
He said they were all you. I'm putting
you and Lina together in a picture.


140
00:10:14.335 --> 00:10:16.913
Come to my office.
We'll discuss a contract.


141
00:10:16.963 --> 00:10:18.915
Thanks, Mr. Simpson!

142
00:10:22.677 --> 00:10:25.847
Are you doing anything
tonight, Miss Lamont?


143
00:10:27.306 --> 00:10:28.974
That's funny.

144
00:10:28.975 --> 00:10:30.518
I'm busy.

145
00:10:35.481 --> 00:10:39.857
<i>DON: Lina and I have had the same
wonderful relationship ever since.</i>


146
00:10:39.986 --> 00:10:44.032
But most important of all,
I continue living up to my motto:


147
00:10:44.365 --> 00:10:45.691
"Dignity.

148
00:10:45.908 --> 00:10:48.076
Always dignity."

149
00:10:48.077 --> 00:10:49.494
(CROWD CHEERING)

150
00:10:49.495 --> 00:10:50.696
Thank you, Don.

151
00:10:50.746 --> 00:10:55.452
And I'm sure you and Lina will continue
making movie history tonight...


152
00:10:55.501 --> 00:11:00.457
in your greatest picture,
<i>The Royal Rascal.</i>


153
00:11:00.715 --> 00:11:03.213
(CROWD CHEERING)

154
00:11:04.051 --> 00:11:05.594
Get enough, boys?

155
00:11:09.599 --> 00:11:11.676
(ORCHESTRA MUSIC PLAYING)

156
00:11:20.651 --> 00:11:22.603
(INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE)

157
00:11:42.798 --> 00:11:44.716
She's so refined...

158
00:11:44.759 --> 00:11:47.303
I think I'll kill myself.

159
00:12:13.746 --> 00:12:16.620
(APPLAUSE)

160
00:12:26.217 --> 00:12:30.638
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.
Thank you, thank you, thank you.


161
00:12:32.431 --> 00:12:35.805
We're thrilled at your
response to <i>The Royal Rascal.</i>


162
00:12:35.851 --> 00:12:40.313
We had fun making it, and we hope
you had fun seeing it tonight.


163
00:12:40.314 --> 00:12:42.232
(APPLAUSE)

164
00:12:43.067 --> 00:12:47.568
We screen actors aren't much
good at speaking in public.


165
00:12:47.613 --> 00:12:50.157
So we'll just act out our thanks.

166
00:12:50.449 --> 00:12:52.822
(APPLAUSE)

167
00:13:00.584 --> 00:13:03.754
- ROD: Hot diggity! It's a smash!
- R.F.: Don, Lina, you were gorgeous!


168
00:13:03.796 --> 00:13:05.139
Lina, you looked pretty
good for a girl.


169
00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:07.792
(SCREECHY VOICE) For heaven's
sake! What's the big idea?


170
00:13:07.842 --> 00:13:11.967
Can't a girl get a word in edgewise?
They're my public too!


171
00:13:12.012 --> 00:13:13.714
The publicity department...

172
00:13:13.723 --> 00:13:17.559
thought it'd be better if Don made
all the speeches for the team.


173
00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:18.761
Why?

174
00:13:18.769 --> 00:13:22.098
You're beautiful. Audiences
think you got a voice to match.


175
00:13:22.106 --> 00:13:25.185
We gotta keep our stars from
looking ridiculous at any cost.


176
00:13:25.234 --> 00:13:28.689
- No one's got that much money.
- What's wrong with the way I talk?


177
00:13:28.739 --> 00:13:32.307
What's the big idea?
Am I dumb or something?


178
00:13:32.908 --> 00:13:36.078
No, it's just that Don's had
so much more experience...


179
00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:39.790
Next time, write me out
a speech. I could memorize it.


180
00:13:39.832 --> 00:13:43.206
Sure. Why don't you recite
the Gettysburg Address?


181
00:13:43.210 --> 00:13:47.961
What do you know about it,
you piano player? Are you anybody?


182
00:13:48.007 --> 00:13:52.428
Donnie, how can you let him talk
to me like that, your fianc√©e?


183
00:13:52.511 --> 00:13:54.008
My fia...

184
00:13:54.263 --> 00:13:57.842
Lina, you've been reading
those fan magazines again.


185
00:13:57.892 --> 00:14:01.266
Look, you shouldn't believe
all that banana oil...


186
00:14:01.270 --> 00:14:03.643
that Dora Bailey dishes out.

187
00:14:03.647 --> 00:14:07.852
Now, try to get this straight:
There is nothing between us.


188
00:14:07.902 --> 00:14:10.651
There has never been
anything between us.


189
00:14:10.654 --> 00:14:14.108
- Just air.
- Oh, Donnie, you don't mean that.


190
00:14:14.158 --> 00:14:16.281
We'll be late for R.F.'s party.

191
00:14:16.327 --> 00:14:20.157
Better go in separate cars to break
up the mobs. Come on, honey.


192
00:14:20.164 --> 00:14:23.117
Ta-ta, Donnie! 
See you there!

193
00:14:24.210 --> 00:14:25.411
"Donnie."

194
00:14:25.711 --> 00:14:28.254
Can't that girl take a gentle hint?

195
00:14:28.255 --> 00:14:31.755
Haven't you heard? She's
irresistible. She told me so.


196
00:14:31.801 --> 00:14:35.301
I can't get her out of my hair.
This romance for publicity...


197
00:14:35.346 --> 00:14:38.015
The price of fame.
You've got the glory.


198
00:14:38.057 --> 00:14:40.058
The little heartaches go with it.

199
00:14:40.059 --> 00:14:44.059
Look at me. I got no glory.
I got no fame. I got no mansions.


200
00:14:44.104 --> 00:14:46.807
I got no money. 
But I've got...

201
00:14:47.066 --> 00:14:49.485
- What have I got?
- I don't know.


202
00:14:49.568 --> 00:14:51.315
I gotta get out of here.

203
00:14:56.659 --> 00:14:58.406
(TIRE BLOWS OUT)

204
00:14:59.870 --> 00:15:02.289
Don't tell me. 
It's a flat tire.

205
00:15:02.331 --> 00:15:05.705
This car hasn't given me
trouble in nearly six hours.


206
00:15:05.709 --> 00:15:07.582
GIRL 1: Hey, there's Don Lockwood!

207
00:15:08.170 --> 00:15:09.713
Hey, give me an autograph!

208
00:15:09.755 --> 00:15:13.334
- BOY 1: Give me your autograph!
- BOY 2: I want a souvenir!


209
00:15:13.384 --> 00:15:15.211
GIRL 2: I want a souvenir too!

210
00:15:15.261 --> 00:15:18.806
DON: Hey! You're playing
rough here! You're tearing my...!


211
00:15:19.139 --> 00:15:21.888
Hey, Cos, do something!
Call me a cab!


212
00:15:21.892 --> 00:15:23.218
You're a cab.

213
00:15:23.686 --> 00:15:25.308
Thanks a lot!

214
00:15:38.450 --> 00:15:39.617
(KATHY SCREAMS)

215
00:15:39.618 --> 00:15:41.320
- Lady, keep driving.
- Get out!


216
00:15:41.328 --> 00:15:44.247
- Everything's all right!
- I'll call a policeman!


217
00:15:44.248 --> 00:15:46.164
- Just a few blocks.
- Don't hurt me!


218
00:15:46.165 --> 00:15:48.585
- I'm not a criminal.
- I don't care...


219
00:15:48.627 --> 00:15:52.422
You are a criminal! I've seen
that face. You're a gangster!


220
00:15:52.423 --> 00:15:56.009
I've seen your picture in the
paper or in the post office.


221
00:15:56.010 --> 00:15:57.257
Officer!

222
00:15:57.261 --> 00:16:01.386
- This man jumped in my car and...
- Why, it's Don Lockwood!


223
00:16:01.432 --> 00:16:04.351
- Don Lockwood?
- How are you? Out for a joy ride?


224
00:16:04.393 --> 00:16:07.893
Just a lift. My car broke down.
I got surrounded by...


225
00:16:07.938 --> 00:16:10.766
- You're a lucky lady. Anything wrong?
- Why, no.


226
00:16:10.774 --> 00:16:12.897
No, I should think not. Good night.

227
00:16:12.943 --> 00:16:14.770
Good night, officer.

228
00:16:15.988 --> 00:16:20.193
Well, thanks for saving
my life. I'll get out now.


229
00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:23.368
I'm driving to Beverly Hills.
Can I drop you someplace?


230
00:16:23.369 --> 00:16:28.076
I'd like to get out of this suit if
you're going by Camden and Sunset.


231
00:16:28.083 --> 00:16:29.705
Yes, I am.

232
00:16:33.464 --> 00:16:36.759
I'd like to know whose
hospitality I'm enjoying.


233
00:16:36.800 --> 00:16:38.752
Selden. Kathy Selden.

234
00:16:38.802 --> 00:16:40.970
Enchanted, Miss Selden.

235
00:16:41.055 --> 00:16:43.097
I'm sorry I frightened you.

236
00:16:43.098 --> 00:16:46.552
I was getting a little too
much love from my fans.


237
00:16:46.602 --> 00:16:49.476
Oh, that's what you
were running away from.


238
00:16:49.521 --> 00:16:52.691
They did that to you?
That's terrible!


239
00:16:55.694 --> 00:16:58.022
Yes. Yes, it is, isn't it?

240
00:16:58.072 --> 00:16:59.774
It is terrible.

241
00:17:00.282 --> 00:17:03.235
Well, we movie stars
get the glory...


242
00:17:03.243 --> 00:17:07.073
I guess we have to take the little
heartaches that go with it.


243
00:17:07.373 --> 00:17:11.498
People think we lead lives
of glamour and romance...


244
00:17:11.543 --> 00:17:13.586
but we're really lonely.

245
00:17:14.630 --> 00:17:16.127
Terribly lonely.

246
00:17:16.131 --> 00:17:20.926
I really can't tell you how sorry
I am about taking you for a criminal.


247
00:17:20.927 --> 00:17:25.224
But it was understandable, under the
circumstances. I knew I'd seen you.


248
00:17:25.225 --> 00:17:27.892
Which of my pictures have you seen?

249
00:17:27.893 --> 00:17:29.185
I don't remember.

250
00:17:29.228 --> 00:17:31.180
I saw one once.

251
00:17:31.772 --> 00:17:34.725
- You saw one once?
- I think you were dueling.


252
00:17:34.775 --> 00:17:36.943
And there was a girl. Lina Lamont.

253
00:17:36.986 --> 00:17:38.984
I don't go to the movies much.

254
00:17:38.988 --> 00:17:42.283
If you've seen one,
you've seen them all.


255
00:17:43.242 --> 00:17:44.443
Thank you.

256
00:17:44.493 --> 00:17:45.865
No offense.

257
00:17:45.911 --> 00:17:48.205
Movies are entertaining
for the masses...


258
00:17:48.247 --> 00:17:51.496
but the personalities on the
screen don't impress me.


259
00:17:51.542 --> 00:17:55.372
They don't talk or act.
They just make a lot of dumb show.


260
00:17:55.421 --> 00:17:57.043
Well, you know.

261
00:17:58.590 --> 00:17:59.791
Like that.

262
00:18:00.300 --> 00:18:02.502
You mean, like what I do.

263
00:18:03.053 --> 00:18:04.596
Well, yes.

264
00:18:04.805 --> 00:18:07.758
Here we are, Sunset and Camden.

265
00:18:09.393 --> 00:18:12.016
Wait, you mean I'm not an actor?

266
00:18:12.021 --> 00:18:14.690
- Pantomime isn't acting?
- Of course not.


267
00:18:14.773 --> 00:18:18.443
Acting means great parts,
wonderful lines, glorious words.


268
00:18:18.444 --> 00:18:19.861
Shakespeare. Ibsen.

269
00:18:19.903 --> 00:18:21.980
What's your lofty
mission in life...


270
00:18:22.031 --> 00:18:25.531
that lets you sneer at
my humble profession?


271
00:18:25.534 --> 00:18:27.486
I'm an actress. On the stage.

272
00:18:27.494 --> 00:18:29.241
Oh, on the stage.

273
00:18:29.288 --> 00:18:31.866
I'd like to see you.
What're you in now?


274
00:18:31.915 --> 00:18:35.335
I could brush up on my English
or bring an interpreter.


275
00:18:35.544 --> 00:18:37.417
That's if they'd let
in a movie actor.


276
00:18:37.463 --> 00:18:40.505
I'm not in a play now.
But I'm going to New York...


277
00:18:40.506 --> 00:18:45.087
You're going to New York, and someday
we'll all hear of you, won't we?


278
00:18:45.095 --> 00:18:48.674
Kathy Selden as Juliet,
as Lady MacBeth, as King Lear!


279
00:18:48.724 --> 00:18:50.301
You'll have to wear a beard!

280
00:18:50.350 --> 00:18:54.020
Laugh if you want, but the stage
is a dignified profession.


281
00:18:54.021 --> 00:18:56.144
Why are you so conceited?

282
00:18:56.190 --> 00:19:00.440
You're nothing but a shadow on film.
You're not flesh and blood.


283
00:19:00.444 --> 00:19:03.067
- Stop!
- What can I do? I'm only a shadow.


284
00:19:03.072 --> 00:19:07.197
Keep away from me! Just because
you're a big movie star...


285
00:19:07.242 --> 00:19:11.161
you expect every girl to faint
at your feet. Don't touch me!


286
00:19:11.162 --> 00:19:13.866
Fear not, sweet lady.
I will not molest you.


287
00:19:13.916 --> 00:19:19.088
I am but a humble Jester. And you?
You are too far above me.


288
00:19:19.379 --> 00:19:21.377
Farewell, Ethel Barrymore.

289
00:19:21.423 --> 00:19:24.675
I must tear myself from your side.

290
00:19:24.676 --> 00:19:26.052
(SUIT RIPPING)

291
00:19:26.053 --> 00:19:28.051
(KATHY LAUGHING)

292
00:19:36.563 --> 00:19:40.688
Kathy: Is this R.F. Simpson's house?
I'm one of the Coconut Grove girls.


293
00:19:40.734 --> 00:19:45.155
- Yes, the floor show. Around the back.
- Oh, I see. Thank you.


294
00:19:47.908 --> 00:19:50.406
(BAND PLAYING TANGO)

295
00:20:08.137 --> 00:20:10.715
- Nice little party, R.F.
- Thanks, Roscoe.


296
00:20:10.764 --> 00:20:13.968
Do you really think you
can get me in the movies?


297
00:20:14.017 --> 00:20:16.219
- I should think so.
- Really?


298
00:20:16.270 --> 00:20:20.100
- MAN: The picture's great.
- WOMAN: There's Don. I loved the picture.


299
00:20:20.190 --> 00:20:23.769
- COSMO: Did you come by way of Australia?
- DON: Hello, Cos. Excuse me.


300
00:20:23.819 --> 00:20:26.898
Cos, tell me the truth.
Am I a good actor?


301
00:20:26.947 --> 00:20:29.775
As long as I work for Monumental,
you're the greatest.


302
00:20:29.783 --> 00:20:32.361
No kidding. You're my pal.
You can tell me.


303
00:20:32.411 --> 00:20:34.784
What's the matter?
Of course, you're good.


304
00:20:34.788 --> 00:20:38.743
Keep telling me from time
to time. I feel a little shaken.


305
00:20:38.792 --> 00:20:40.494
- The new Don Lockwood.
- R.F.: Don!


306
00:20:40.919 --> 00:20:44.293
- Hi, R.F.
- It's colossal. Where have you been?


307
00:20:44.339 --> 00:20:47.175
There you are. Where were you?
I was lonely.


308
00:20:47.176 --> 00:20:48.377
Hello, Lina.

309
00:20:48.427 --> 00:20:50.094
Okay, fellas. Hold it.

310
00:20:50.095 --> 00:20:51.262
(MUSIC STOPS)

311
00:20:51.263 --> 00:20:54.056
Together again, my two
little stars, Don and Lina.


312
00:20:54.057 --> 00:20:56.476
No kidding, folks,
aren't they great?


313
00:20:58.770 --> 00:21:00.893
All right, open that screen.

314
00:21:01.440 --> 00:21:05.233
- A movie? We just saw one.
- Gotta show one at a party. It's a law.


315
00:21:05.234 --> 00:21:08.154
Everybody, I've got a
few surprises for you.


316
00:21:08.155 --> 00:21:10.528
All right, sit down, sit down.

317
00:21:10.616 --> 00:21:12.363
This'll make you laugh.

318
00:21:12.451 --> 00:21:15.951
There's a madman coming into
my office for months, and...


319
00:21:16.079 --> 00:21:18.998
- You got that gadget working?
- PROJECTIONIST: All set.


320
00:21:18.999 --> 00:21:21.076
R.F.: Okay, let her go.

321
00:21:26.798 --> 00:21:28.466
<i>Hello.</i>

322
00:21:28.884 --> 00:21:33.430
<i>This is a demonstration
of a talking picture.</i>


323
00:21:33.639 --> 00:21:38.684
<i>Notice, it is a picture
of me and I am talking.</i>


324
00:21:38.685 --> 00:21:43.061
<i>Note how my lips and the
sound issuing from them...</i>


325
00:21:43.065 --> 00:21:45.734
<i>are synchronized together...</i>

326
00:21:45.776 --> 00:21:48.729
<i>in perfect unison.</i>

327
00:21:49.321 --> 00:21:52.489
- Who's that?
- Somebody's talking behind that screen.


328
00:21:52.490 --> 00:21:55.069
Come out from behind
that screen, Mr. Simpson.


329
00:21:55.160 --> 00:21:56.953
Oh, no. I'm right here.

330
00:21:59.748 --> 00:22:03.498
<i>My voice has been
recorded on a record.</i>


331
00:22:03.585 --> 00:22:05.787
<i>A talking picture.</i>

332
00:22:06.213 --> 00:22:07.835
<i>Thank you.</i>

333
00:22:07.881 --> 00:22:09.207
<i>Goodbye.</i>

334
00:22:12.636 --> 00:22:13.837
Well?

335
00:22:14.179 --> 00:22:16.928
- It's just a toy.
- It's a scream!


336
00:22:17.015 --> 00:22:20.139
- It's vulgar.
- You think they'll ever use it?


337
00:22:20.185 --> 00:22:24.354
I doubt it. Warners is making a
picture with it, <i>The Jazz Singer.</i>


338
00:22:24.355 --> 00:22:27.856
- They'll lose their shirts.
- It'll never amount to a thing.


339
00:22:27.859 --> 00:22:29.857
They said that about the
horseless carriage.


340
00:22:29.861 --> 00:22:32.234
Let's get on with the show.
Okay, boys.


341
00:22:32.281 --> 00:22:34.483
Come on, my little starlets.

342
00:22:34.700 --> 00:22:37.242
R.F.: I have a surprise.
A very special cake.


343
00:22:37.243 --> 00:22:40.118
I want you kiddies to
have the first piece.


344
00:22:41.832 --> 00:22:44.410
(CROWD APPLAUDS)

345
00:22:45.419 --> 00:22:48.589
Well! If it isn't Ethel Barrymore!

346
00:22:54.219 --> 00:22:59.550
I do hope you'll favor us with something
special. Say, Hamlet's soliloquy...


347
00:22:59.558 --> 00:23:02.887
or a scene from Romeo
and Juliet? Don't be shy.


348
00:23:02.936 --> 00:23:07.016
You make about the prettiest
Juliet I've ever seen. Really.


349
00:23:10.152 --> 00:23:13.777
<i>(SINGING) All I do is dream of you
The whole night through.</i>


350
00:23:14.197 --> 00:23:17.992
<i>With the dawn I still go on
Dreaming of you.</i>


351
00:23:18.076 --> 00:23:20.404
<i>You're every thought
You're everything.</i>


352
00:23:20.454 --> 00:23:22.076
<i>You're every song I ever sing.</i>

353
00:23:22.122 --> 00:23:25.997
<i>Summer, winter, autumn and spring.</i>

354
00:23:26.001 --> 00:23:30.001
<i>And were there more than
Twenty-four hours a day.</i>


355
00:23:30.255 --> 00:23:33.925
<i>They'd be spent in sweet content
Dreaming away.</i>


356
00:23:34.134 --> 00:23:36.302
<i>When skies are gray
When skies are blue.</i>


357
00:23:36.303 --> 00:23:38.301
<i>Morning, noon and nighttime too.</i>

358
00:23:38.305 --> 00:23:42.510
<i>All I do the whole day through
Is dream of you.</i>


359
00:24:04.539 --> 00:24:06.332
<i>It's the cat's meow!</i>

360
00:24:09.669 --> 00:24:13.715
<i>All I do the whole day through
Is dream of you.</i>


361
00:24:13.799 --> 00:24:16.468
- I had to tell you how good you were.
- Excuse me.


362
00:24:16.510 --> 00:24:20.135
Now that I know where you live,
I'd like to see you home.


363
00:24:20.180 --> 00:24:23.850
- Listen, Mr. Lockwood...
- Say, who is this dame anyway?


364
00:24:23.851 --> 00:24:26.894
Someone lofty and far above us all.

365
00:24:26.895 --> 00:24:31.475
She couldn't learn anything from
the movies. She's a stage actress.


366
00:24:31.525 --> 00:24:34.854
Here's one thing I've
learned from the movies!


367
00:24:35.529 --> 00:24:38.653
(LINA SOB AND SCREAMS)

368
00:24:38.865 --> 00:24:41.909
- I'll kill her!
- Lina, she was aiming at me!


369
00:24:41.952 --> 00:24:44.655
- You never looked lovelier.
- It was an accident.


370
00:24:44.704 --> 00:24:46.952
It happens to me five
or six times a day.


371
00:24:46.998 --> 00:24:48.450
Where is she?

372
00:24:49.084 --> 00:24:50.376
Donnie?

373
00:24:52.003 --> 00:24:53.170
(WOMEN SCREAM)

374
00:24:53.171 --> 00:24:55.465
Excuse me. Where'd Miss Selden go?

375
00:24:55.507 --> 00:24:59.257
She grabbed her things and
bolted. Anything I can do?


376
00:24:59.302 --> 00:25:02.130
Sorry. I don't have
time to find out.


377
00:25:05.183 --> 00:25:06.384
Kathy!

378
00:25:06.393 --> 00:25:07.890
Hey, Kathy!

379
00:25:09.855 --> 00:25:11.227
Hey!

380
00:25:37.257 --> 00:25:40.301
DIRECTOR 1: Keep that action going.
More steam in the kettle!


381
00:25:40.343 --> 00:25:42.716
More action, boys.
A little more rhythm.


382
00:25:42.762 --> 00:25:44.680
More steam and more water.

383
00:25:44.931 --> 00:25:46.678
- Hi, Maxie.
- MAXIE: Hi, Don.


384
00:25:47.642 --> 00:25:49.594
- Good morning, fellas.
- Hiya, Don.


385
00:25:49.644 --> 00:25:51.562
Did you read Variety today?

386
00:25:51.563 --> 00:25:55.518
"First talking picture, The Jazz Singer.
All-time smash end of first week."


387
00:25:55.525 --> 00:25:58.695
- All-time flop end of the second.
- We start today.


388
00:25:58.737 --> 00:26:00.029
- Good luck.
- Thanks.


389
00:26:00.071 --> 00:26:03.866
I'm now Count Pierre de Bataille,
known as the Duelling Cavalier.


390
00:26:03.909 --> 00:26:06.703
- What's it about?
- It's a French Revolution story.


391
00:26:06.745 --> 00:26:08.663
You're a French aristocrat.

392
00:26:08.747 --> 00:26:12.326
She's a simple girl of the people
and won't even give you a tumble.


393
00:26:12.334 --> 00:26:14.377
Well, it's a living.

394
00:26:15.045 --> 00:26:16.462
COSMO: Good morning.

395
00:26:17.047 --> 00:26:19.215
DIRECTOR 2: Keep the
background moving. Hit him.


396
00:26:19.257 --> 00:26:20.798
Come on. Knock him down!

397
00:26:20.799 --> 00:26:23.549
Get up there and hit
him again. Hurry up!


398
00:26:23.595 --> 00:26:27.095
Why bother to shoot this? Release
the old one under a new title.


399
00:26:27.140 --> 00:26:29.642
You've seen one,
you've seen them all.


400
00:26:29.643 --> 00:26:31.971
- Why'd you say that?
- What's the matter?


401
00:26:31.978 --> 00:26:34.977
That's what that Kathy Selden
said to me that night.


402
00:26:34.981 --> 00:26:38.355
That's three weeks ago.
You still thinking about that?


403
00:26:38.527 --> 00:26:42.231
- I can't get her out of my mind.
- How could you?


404
00:26:42.280 --> 00:26:45.700
She's the first dame who hasn't
fallen for you since you were 4.


405
00:26:45.784 --> 00:26:47.327
She's on my conscience.

406
00:26:47.369 --> 00:26:49.410
It's not your fault
she lost her job.


407
00:26:49.411 --> 00:26:51.910
- I've got to find her.
- You've been trying to.


408
00:26:51.915 --> 00:26:54.413
Short of sending out
bloodhounds and a posse.


409
00:26:54.459 --> 00:26:56.206
Come on, now. Snap out of it.

410
00:26:56.294 --> 00:26:58.212
You can't let this get you down.

411
00:26:58.296 --> 00:27:01.839
You're Donald Lockwood. Donald
Lockwood's an actor, isn't he?


412
00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:03.918
What's the first thing
an actor learns?


413
00:27:03.927 --> 00:27:09.258
"The show must go on, come rain,
come shine, come snow, come sleet!"


414
00:27:09.599 --> 00:27:13.185
(SPEAKS IN ITALIAN)

415
00:27:13.186 --> 00:27:14.433
Yeah.

416
00:27:14.688 --> 00:27:16.765
<i>The world's so full
Of a number of things.</i>


417
00:27:16.815 --> 00:27:19.359
<i>I'm sure we should all
Be as happy as...</i>


418
00:27:19.401 --> 00:27:21.103
<i>But are we? No.</i>

419
00:27:21.152 --> 00:27:22.353
<i>Definitely, no.</i>

420
00:27:22.362 --> 00:27:25.065
<i>Positively, no
Decidedly, no.</i>


421
00:27:27.659 --> 00:27:29.907
<i>Short people have long faces.</i>

422
00:27:29.953 --> 00:27:31.951
<i>Long people have short faces.</i>

423
00:27:31.955 --> 00:27:35.082
<i>Big people have little humor
Little people have no humor at all</i>


424
00:27:35.083 --> 00:27:36.292
(DON CHUCKLES)

425
00:27:36.293 --> 00:27:39.667
<i>In the words of that immortal bard
Samuel J. Snodgrass.</i>


426
00:27:39.671 --> 00:27:42.249
<i>As he was being led
To the guillotine</i>


427
00:27:43.049 --> 00:27:46.128
<i>(SINGING) Make 'em laugh
Make 'em laugh.</i>


428
00:27:46.136 --> 00:27:49.055
<i>Don't you know everyone
wants to laugh, ha, ha.</i>


429
00:27:49.514 --> 00:27:52.467
<i>My dad said, "Be an actor, my son".</i>

430
00:27:52.892 --> 00:27:55.140
<i>"But be a comical one".</i>

431
00:27:55.186 --> 00:27:58.139
<i>They'll be standin' in lines.</i>

432
00:27:58.231 --> 00:28:01.560
<i>For those old
honky-tonk monkeyshines.</i>


433
00:28:01.651 --> 00:28:04.695
<i>Now you could study Shakespeare
And be quite elite.</i>


434
00:28:04.738 --> 00:28:07.612
<i>And you could charm the critics
And have nothing to eat.</i>


435
00:28:07.616 --> 00:28:10.569
<i>Just slip on a banana peel
The world's at your feet.</i>


436
00:28:10.619 --> 00:28:12.286
<i>Make 'em laugh
Make 'em laugh.</i>


437
00:28:12.287 --> 00:28:13.454
<i>Make 'em laugh.</i>

438
00:28:13.455 --> 00:28:14.656
Make...?

439
00:28:15.081 --> 00:28:16.578
<i>Make 'em laugh.</i>

440
00:28:16.583 --> 00:28:20.083
<i>Don't you know everyone
wants to laugh?</i>


441
00:28:20.086 --> 00:28:23.210
<i>My Grandpa said,
"Go out and tell 'em a joke"</i>


442
00:28:23.673 --> 00:28:26.171
<i>"but give it plenty of hoke".</i>

443
00:28:26.217 --> 00:28:28.920
<i>Make 'em roar
Make 'em scream.</i>


444
00:28:28.970 --> 00:28:32.265
<i>Take a fall, butt a wall
Split a seam.</i>


445
00:28:32.307 --> 00:28:35.351
<i>You start off by pretending
You're a dancer with grace.</i>


446
00:28:35.393 --> 00:28:38.392
<i>You wiggle till they're giggling
All over the place.</i>


447
00:28:38.438 --> 00:28:41.232
<i>And then you get
A great big custard pie in the face.</i>


448
00:28:41.274 --> 00:28:42.851
<i>Make 'em laugh
Make 'em laugh.</i>


449
00:28:42.901 --> 00:28:44.523
<i>Make 'em laugh.</i>

450
00:28:45.820 --> 00:28:47.442
<i>Make 'em laugh.</i>

451
00:28:47.447 --> 00:28:48.906
<i>Don't ya...
All the...</i>


452
00:28:48.907 --> 00:28:50.199
<i>What...?</i>

453
00:28:50.825 --> 00:28:52.117
<i>My Dad...</i>

